# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: structured-clone
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:structured-clone/object-copying] In object-oriented programming, **object copying** is creating a copy of an existing object, a unit of data in object-oriented programming.
[src:structured-clone/object-copying] The resulting object is called an *object copy* or simply *copy* of the original object.
[src:structured-clone/object-copying] Copying is basic but has subtleties and can have significant overhead.
[src:structured-clone/object-copying] There are several ways to copy an object, most commonly by a copy constructor or cloning.
[src:structured-clone/object-copying] Copying is done mostly so the copy can be modified or moved, or the current value preserved.
[src:structured-clone/object-copying] If either of these is unneeded, a reference to the original data is sufficient and more efficient, as no copying occurs.
[src:structured-clone/object-copying] Objects in general store composite data.
[src:structured-clone/object-copying] While in simple cases copying can be done by allocating a new, uninitialized object and copying all fields (attributes) from the original object, in more complex cases this does not result in desired behavior.
[src:structured-clone/object-copying] The design goal of most objects is to give the resemblance of being made out of one monolithic block even though most are not.
[src:structured-clone/object-copying] As objects are made up of several different parts, copying becomes nontrivial.
[src:structured-clone/object-copying] Several strategies exist to treat this problem.
[src:structured-clone/object-copying] Consider an object A, which contains fields xi (more concretely, consider if A is a string and xi is an array of its characters).
[src:structured-clone/object-copying] There are different strategies for making a copy of A, referred to as *shallow copy* and *deep copy*.
[src:structured-clone/object-copying] Many languages allow generic copying by one or either strategy, defining either one *copy* operation or separate *shallow copy* and *deep copy* operations.
[src:structured-clone/object-copying] Note that even shallower is to use a reference to the existing object A, in which case there is no new object, only a new reference.
[src:structured-clone/object-copying] The terminology of *shallow copy* and *deep copy* dates to Smalltalk-80.
[src:structured-clone/object-copying] Variables referring to same area of memory.
[src:structured-clone/object-copying] One method of copying an object is the *shallow copy*.
[src:structured-clone/object-copying] In that case a new object B is created, and the fields values of A are copied over to B.
[src:structured-clone/object-copying] This is also known as a *field-by-field copy*, *field-for-field copy*, or *field copy*.
[src:structured-clone/object-copying] If the field value is a reference to an object (e.g., a memory address) it copies the reference, hence referring to the same object as A does, and if the field value is a primitive type, it copies the value of the primitive type.
[src:structured-clone/object-copying] In languages without primitive types (where everything is an object), all fields of the copy B are references to the same objects as the fields of original A.
[src:structured-clone/object-copying] The referenced objects are thus *shared*, so if one of these objects is modified (from A or B), the change is visible in the other.
[src:structured-clone/object-copying] Shallow copies are simple and typically cheap, as they can usually be implemented by simply copying the bits exactly.
[src:structured-clone/object-copying] An alternative is a deep copy, meaning that fields are dereferenced: rather than references to objects being copied, new copy of objects are created for any referenced objects, and references to these are placed in B.
[src:structured-clone/object-copying] Later modifications to the contents remain unique to A or B, as the contents are not shared.
[src:structured-clone/object-copying] In more complex cases, some fields in a copy should have shared values with the original object (as in a shallow copy), corresponding to an "association" relationship; some fields should have copies (as in a deep copy), corresponding to an "aggregation" relationship.
[src:structured-clone/object-copying] In these cases a custom implementation of copying is generally required; this issue and solution dates to Smalltalk-80.
[src:structured-clone/object-copying] Alternatively, fields can be marked as requiring a shallow copy or deep copy, and copy operations automatically generated (likewise for comparison operations).
[src:structured-clone/object-copying] This is not implemented in most object-oriented languages, however, though there is partial support in Eiffel.
[src:structured-clone/object-copying] Nearly all object-oriented programming languages provide some way to copy objects.
[src:structured-clone/object-copying] As most languages do not provide most objects for programs, a programmer must define how an object should be copied, just as they must define if two objects are identical or even comparable in the first place.
[src:structured-clone/object-copying] Many languages provide some default behavior.
[src:structured-clone/object-copying] How copying is solved varies from language to language, and what concept of an object it has.
[src:structured-clone/object-copying] A lazy copy is an implementation of a deep copy.
[src:structured-clone/object-copying] When initially copying an object, a (fast) shallow copy is used.
[src:structured-clone/object-copying] A counter is also used to track how many objects share the data.
[src:structured-clone/object-copying] When the program wants to modify an object, it can determine if the data is shared (by examining the counter) and can do a deep copy if needed.
[src:structured-clone/object-copying] Lazy copy looks to the outside just as a deep copy, but takes advantage of the speed of a shallow copy whenever possible.
[src:structured-clone/object-copying] The downside are rather high but constant base costs because of the counter.
[src:structured-clone/object-copying] Also, in certain situations, circular references can cause problems.
[src:structured-clone/object-copying] In C++, a lazy copy occurs by default when invoking the copy constructor.
[src:structured-clone/object-copying] The following presents examples for one of the most widely used object-oriented languages, Java, which should cover nearly every way that an object-oriented language can treat this problem.
[src:structured-clone/object-copying] Unlike in C++, objects in Java are always accessed indirectly through references.
[src:structured-clone/object-copying] Objects are never created implicitly but instead are always passed or assigned by a reference variable.
[src:structured-clone/object-copying] (Methods in Java are always *pass by value*, however, it is the value of the reference variable that is being passed.) The Java Virtual Machine manages garbage collection so that objects are cleaned up after they are no longer reachable.
[src:structured-clone/object-copying] There is no automatic way to copy any given object in Java.
[src:structured-clone/object-copying] Copying is usually performed by a clone() method of a class.
[src:structured-clone/object-copying] This method usually, in turn, calls the clone() method of its parent class to obtain a copy, and then does any custom copying procedures.
[src:structured-clone/object-copying] Eventually this gets to the clone() method of `Object` (the uppermost class), which creates a new instance of the same class as the object and copies all the fields to the new instance (a "shallow copy").
[src:structured-clone/object-copying] If this method is used, the class must implement the `Cloneable` marker interface, or else it will throw a "Clone Not Supported Exception".
[src:structured-clone/object-copying] After obtaining a copy from the parent class, a class' own clone() method may then provide custom cloning capability, like deep copying (i.e. duplicate some of the structures referred to by the object) or giving the new instance a new unique ID.
[src:structured-clone/object-copying] The return type of clone() is `Object`, but implementers of a clone method could write the type of the object being cloned instead due to Java's support for covariant return types.
[src:structured-clone/object-copying] One advantage of using clone() is that since it is an overridable method, we can call clone() on any object, and it will use the clone() method of its class, without the calling code needing to know what that class is (which would be needed with a copy constructor).
[src:structured-clone/object-copying] A disadvantage is that one often cannot access the clone() method on an abstract type.
[src:structured-clone/object-copying] Most interfaces and abstract classes in Java do not specify a public clone() method.
[src:structured-clone/object-copying] Thus, often the only way to use the clone() method is if the class of an object is known, which is contrary to the abstraction principle of using the most generic type possible.
[src:structured-clone/object-copying] For example, if one has a List reference in Java, one cannot invoke clone() on that reference because List specifies no public clone() method.
[src:structured-clone/object-copying] Implementations of List like Array List and Linked List all generally have clone() methods, but it is inconvenient and bad abstraction to carry around the class type of an object.
[src:structured-clone/object-copying] Another way to copy objects in Java is to serialize them through the `Serializable` interface.
[src:structured-clone/object-copying] This is typically used for persistence and wire protocol purposes, but it does create copies of objects and, unlike clone, a deep copy that gracefully handles cycled graphs of objects is readily available with minimal effort from a programmer.
[src:structured-clone/object-copying] Both of these methods suffer from a notable problem: the constructor is not used for objects copied with clone or serialization.
[src:structured-clone/object-copying] This can lead to bugs with improperly initialized data, prevents the use of `final` member fields, and makes maintenance challenging.
[src:structured-clone/object-copying] Some utilities attempt to overcome these issues by using reflection to deep copy objects, such as the deep-cloning library.
[src:structured-clone/object-copying] Runtime objects in Eiffel are accessible either indirectly through references or as *expanded* objects which fields are embedded within the objects that use them.
[src:structured-clone/object-copying] That is, fields of an object are stored either externally or internally.
[src:structured-clone/object-copying] The Eiffel class `ANY` contains features for shallow and deep copying and cloning of objects.
[src:structured-clone/object-copying] All Eiffel classes inherit from `ANY`, so these features are available within all classes, and are applicable both to reference and expanded objects.
[src:structured-clone/object-copying] The `copy` feature effects a shallow, field-by-field copy from one object to another.
[src:structured-clone/object-copying] If `y` were copied to `x`, then the same objects referenced by `y` before the application of `copy`, will also be referenced by `x` after the `copy` feature completes.
[src:structured-clone/object-copying] To effect the creation of a new object which is a shallow duplicate of `y`, the feature `twin` is used.
[src:structured-clone/object-copying] In this case, one new object is created with its fields identical to those of the source.
[src:structured-clone/object-copying] The feature `twin` relies on the feature `copy`, which can be redefined in descendants of `ANY`, if needed.
[src:structured-clone/object-copying] The result of `twin` is of the anchored type `like Current`.
[src:structured-clone/object-copying] Deep copying and creating deep twins can be done using the features `deep_copy` and `deep_twin`, again inherited from class `ANY`.
[src:structured-clone/object-copying] These features have the potential to create many new objects, because they duplicate all the objects in an entire object structure.
[src:structured-clone/object-copying] Because new duplicate objects are created instead of simply copying references to existing objects, deep operations will become a source of performance issues more readily than shallow operations.
[src:structured-clone/object-copying] In C#, rather than using the interface `ICloneable`, a generic extension method can be used to create a deep copy using reflection.
[src:structured-clone/object-copying] This has two advantages: First, it provides the flexibility to copy every object without having to specify each property and variable to be copied manually.
[src:structured-clone/object-copying] Second, because the type is generic, the compiler ensures that the destination object and the source object have the same type.
[src:structured-clone/object-copying] In Objective-C, the methods `copy` and `mutableCopy` are inherited by all objects and intended for performing copies; the latter is for creating a mutable type of the original object.
[src:structured-clone/object-copying] These methods in turn call the `copyWithZone` and `mutableCopyWithZone` methods, respectively, to perform the copying.
[src:structured-clone/object-copying] An object must implement the corresponding `copyWithZone` method to be copyable.
[src:structured-clone/object-copying] In OCaml, the library function Oo.copy performs shallow copying of an object.
[src:structured-clone/object-copying] In Python, the library's copy module provides shallow copy and deep copy of objects through the `copy()` and `deepcopy()` functions, respectively.
[src:structured-clone/object-copying] Programmers may define special methods `__copy__()` and `__deepcopy__()` in an object to provide custom copying implementation.
[src:structured-clone/object-copying] In Ruby, all objects inherit two methods for performing shallow copies, clone and dup.
[src:structured-clone/object-copying] The two methods differ in that `clone` copies an object's tainted state, frozen state, and any singleton methods it may have, whereas `dup` copies only its tainted state.
[src:structured-clone/object-copying] In Rust, structs can implement the `clone` method using the `Clone` trait.
[src:structured-clone/object-copying] In Perl, nested structures are stored by the use of references, thus a developer can either loop over the entire structure and re-reference the data or use the `dclone()` function from the module Storable.
[src:structured-clone/object-copying] In VBA, an assignment of variables of type `Object` is a shallow copy, an assignment for all other types (numeric types, String, user defined types, arrays) is a deep copy.
[src:structured-clone/object-copying] So the keyword `Set` for an assignment signals a shallow copy and the (optional) keyword `Let` signals a deep copy.
[src:structured-clone/object-copying] There is no built-in method for deep copies of Objects in VBA.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] When the resulting series of bits is reread according to the serialization format, it can be used to create a semantically identical clone of the original object.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] For many complex objects, such as those that make extensive use of references, this process is not straightforward.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] Serialization of objects does not include any of their associated methods with which they were previously linked.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] This process of serializing an object is also called *marshalling* in some situations.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] The opposite operation, extracting a data structure from a series of bytes, is ***deserialization*** (also called ***unserialization*** or ***unmarshalling***).
[src:structured-clone/serialization] In networking equipment hardware, the part that is responsible for serialization and deserialization is commonly called SerDes.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] For some of these features to be useful, architecture independence must be maintained.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] For example, for maximal use of distribution, a computer running on a different hardware architecture should be able to reliably reconstruct a serialized data stream, regardless of endianness.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] This means that the simpler and faster procedure of directly copying the memory layout of the data structure cannot work reliably for all architectures.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] Serializing the data structure in an architecture-independent format means preventing the problems of byte ordering, memory layout, or simply different ways of representing data structures in different programming languages.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] Inherent to any serialization scheme is that, because the encoding of the data is by definition serial, extracting one part of the serialized data structure requires that the entire object be read from start to end, and reconstructed.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] In many applications, this linearity is an asset, because it enables simple, common I/O interfaces to be utilized to hold and pass on the state of an object.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] In applications where higher performance is an issue, it can make sense to expend more effort to deal with a more complex, non-linear storage organization.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] Even on a single machine, primitive pointer objects are too fragile to save because the objects to which they point may be reloaded to a different location in memory.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] To deal with this, the serialization process includes a step called *unswizzling* or *pointer unswizzling*, where direct pointer references are converted to references based on name or position.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] The deserialization process includes an inverse step called *pointer swizzling*.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] It is not necessary to actually build the prior copy because differences can be detected on the fly, a technique called differential execution.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] This is useful in the programming of user interfaces whose contents are time-varying — graphical objects can be created, removed, altered, or made to handle input events without necessarily having to write separate code to do those things.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] Serialization breaks the opacity of an abstract data type by potentially exposing private implementation details.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] Trivial implementations which serialize all data members may violate encapsulation.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] To discourage competitors from making compatible products, publishers of proprietary software often keep the details of their programs' serialization formats a trade secret.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] Some deliberately obfuscate or even encrypt the serialized data.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] Yet, interoperability requires that applications be able to understand each other's serialization formats.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] Therefore, remote method call architectures such as CORBA define their serialization formats in detail.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] Many institutions, such as archives and libraries, attempt to future proof their backup archives—in particular, database dumps—by storing them in some relatively human-readable serialized format.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] The Xerox Network Systems Courier technology in the early 1980s influenced the first widely adopted standard.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] Sun Microsystems published the External Data Representation (XDR) in 1987.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] XDR is an open format, and standardized as STD 67 (RFC 4506) by IETF.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] In the late 1990s, a push to provide an alternative to the standard serialization protocols started: XML, an SGML subset, was used to produce a human-readable text-based encoding.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] Such an encoding can be useful for persistent objects that may be read and understood by humans or communicated to other systems regardless of programming language.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] It has the disadvantage of losing the more compact, byte-stream-based encoding, but by this point larger storage and transmission capacities made file size less of a concern than in the early days of computing.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] In the 2000s, XML was often used for asynchronous transfer of structured data between client and server in Ajax web applications.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] XML is an open format and standardized as a W3C recommendation.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] JSON is a lightweight plain-text alternative to XML and is also commonly used for client-server communication in web applications.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] JSON is based on JavaScript syntax but is independent of JavaScript and supported in many other programming languages.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] YAML is a strict superset of JSON and includes additional features such as a data type tags, support for cyclic data structures, indentation-sensitive syntax, and multiple forms of scalar data quoting.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] Property lists are used for serialization by NeXTSTEP, GNUstep, macOS, and iOS frameworks.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] *Property list*, or *p-list* for short, doesn't refer to a single serialization format but instead several different variants, some human-readable and one binary.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] For large volume scientific datasets, such as satellite data and output of numerical climate, weather, or ocean models, specific binary serialization standards have been developed, e.g.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] Several object-oriented programming languages directly support *object serialization* (or *object archival*), either by syntactic sugar elements or providing a standard interface for doing so.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] The languages which do so include Ruby, Smalltalk, Python, PHP, Objective-C, Delphi, Java, and the .NET family of languages.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] There are also libraries available that add serialization support to languages that lack native support for it.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] C and C++ do not provide serialization as any sort of high-level construct, but both languages support writing any of the built-in data types, as well as plain old data structs, as binary data.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] As such, it is usually trivial to write custom serialization functions.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] Moreover, compiler-based solutions, such as the ODB ORM system for C++ and the gSOAP toolkit for C and C++, are capable of automatically producing serialization code with few or no modifications to class declarations.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] Other popular serialization frameworks are Boost.Serialization from the Boost Framework, the S11n framework, and Cereal.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] MFC framework (Microsoft) also provides serialization methodology as part of its Document-View architecture.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] With the introduction of reflective programming to C++26, serialization has been greatly simplified.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] Reflection allows for compile-time serialization of, for instance, JSON into a `struct` with corresponding structure.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] CFML allows data structures to be serialized to WDDX with the `<cfwddx>` tag and to JSON with the SerializeJSON() function.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] Delphi provides a built-in mechanism for serialization of components (also called persistent objects), which is fully integrated with its IDE.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] The component's contents are saved to a DFM file and reloaded on-the-fly.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] Go natively supports unmarshalling/marshalling of JSON and XML data.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] There are also third-party modules that support YAML and Protocol Buffers.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] In Haskell, serialization is supported for types that are members of the Read and Show type classes.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] Every type that is a member of the `Read` type class defines a function that will extract the data from the string representation of the dumped data.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] The `Show` type class, in turn, contains the `show` function from which a string representation of the object can be generated.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] The programmer need not define the functions explicitly—merely declaring a type to be deriving Read or deriving Show, or both, can make the compiler generate the appropriate functions for many cases (but not all: function types, for example, cannot automatically derive Show or Read).
[src:structured-clone/serialization] The auto-generated instance for Show also produces valid source code, so the same Haskell value can be generated by running the code produced by show in, for example, a Haskell interpreter.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] For more efficient serialization, there are haskell libraries that allow high-speed serialization in binary format, e.g. binary.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] Java provides automatic serialization which requires that the object be marked by implementing the `java.io.Serializable` interface.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] Implementing the interface marks the class as "okay to serialize", and Java then handles serialization internally.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] There are no serialization methods defined on the `Serializable` interface, but a serializable class can optionally define methods with certain special names and signatures that if defined, will be called as part of the serialization/deserialization process.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] The language also allows the developer to override the serialization process more thoroughly by implementing another interface, the `Externalizable` interface, which includes two special methods that are used to save and restore the object's state.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] There are three primary reasons why objects are not serializable by default and must implement the `Serializable` interface to access Java's serialization mechanism.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] Firstly, not all objects capture useful semantics in a serialized state.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] For example, a `Thread` object is tied to the state of the current JVM.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] There is no context in which a deserialized `Thread` object would maintain useful semantics.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] Secondly, the serialized state of an object forms part of its class' compatibility contract.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] Maintaining compatibility between versions of serializable classes requires additional effort and consideration.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] Therefore, making a class serializable needs to be a deliberate design decision and not a default condition.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] Lastly, serialization allows access to non-transient private members of a class that are not otherwise accessible.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] Classes containing sensitive information (for example, a password) should not be serializable nor externalizable.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] The standard encoding method uses a recursive graph-based translation of the object's class descriptor and serializable fields into a byte stream.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] Primitives as well as non-transient, non-static referenced objects are encoded into the stream.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] Each object that is referenced by the serialized object via a field that is not marked as `transient` must also be serialized; and if any object in the complete graph of non-transient object references is not serializable, then serialization will fail.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] The developer can influence this behavior by marking objects as transient, or by redefining the serialization for an object so that some portion of the reference graph is truncated and not serialized.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] Java does not use constructor to serialize objects.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] It is possible to serialize Java objects through JDBC and store them into a database.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] While Swing components do implement the Serializable interface, they are not guaranteed to be portable between different versions of the Java Virtual Machine.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] As such, a Swing component, or any component which inherits it, may be serialized to a byte stream, but it is not guaranteed that this will be re-constitutable on another machine.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] Since ECMAScript 5.1, JavaScript has included the built-in `JSON` object and its methods `JSON.parse()` and `JSON.stringify()`.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] Although JSON is originally based on a subset of JavaScript, there are boundary cases where JSON is not valid JavaScript.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] Specifically, JSON allows the Unicode line terminators U+2028 LINE SEPARATOR and U+2029 PARAGRAPH SEPARATOR to appear unescaped in quoted strings, while ECMAScript 2018 and older does not.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] Julia implements serialization through the `serialize()` / `deserialize()` modules, intended to work within the same version of Julia, and/or instance of the same system image.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] The `HDF5.jl` package offers a more stable alternative, using a documented format and common library with wrappers for different languages, while the default serialization format is suggested to have been designed rather with maximal performance for network communication in mind.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] Generally a Lisp data structure can be serialized with the functions "`read`" and "`print`".
[src:structured-clone/serialization] A variable foo containing, for example, a list of arrays would be printed by `(print foo)`.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] Similarly an object can be read from a stream named s by `(read s)`.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] These two parts of the Lisp implementation are called the Printer and the Reader.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] The output of "`print`" is human readable; it uses lists demarked by parentheses, for example: `(4 2.9 "x" y)`.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] In many types of Lisp, including Common Lisp, the printer cannot represent every type of data because it is not clear how to do so.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] In Common Lisp for example the printer cannot print CLOS objects.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] Instead the programmer may write a method on the generic function `print-object`, this will be invoked when the object is printed.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] This is somewhat similar to the method used in Ruby.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] Lisp code itself is written in the syntax of the reader, called read syntax.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] Most languages use separate and different parsers to deal with code and data, Lisp only uses one.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] A file containing lisp code may be read into memory as a data structure, transformed by another program, then possibly executed or written out, such as in a read–eval–print loop.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] Not all readers/writers support cyclic, recursive or shared structures.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] .NET has several serializers designed by Microsoft.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] There are also many serializers by third parties.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] OCaml's standard library provides marshalling through the `Marshal` module and the Pervasives functions `output_value` and `input_value`.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] While OCaml programming is statically type-checked, uses of the `Marshal` module may break type guarantees, as there is no way to check whether an unmarshalled stream represents objects of the expected type.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] In OCaml it is difficult to marshal a function or a data structure which contains a function (e.g. an object which contains a method), because executable code in functions cannot be transmitted across different programs.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] (There is a flag to marshal the code position of a function but it can only be unmarshalled in exactly the same program).
[src:structured-clone/serialization] The standard marshalling functions can preserve sharing and handle cyclic data, which can be configured by a flag.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] Several Perl modules available from CPAN provide serialization mechanisms, including `Storable` , `JSON::XS` and `FreezeThaw`.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] Storable includes functions to serialize and deserialize Perl data structures to and from files or Perl scalars.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] In addition to serializing directly to files, `Storable` includes the `freeze` function to return a serialized copy of the data packed into a scalar, and `thaw` to deserialize such a scalar.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] This is useful for sending a complex data structure over a network socket or storing it in a database.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] When serializing structures with `Storable`, there are network safe functions that always store their data in a format that is readable on any computer at a small cost of speed.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] These functions are named `nstore`, `nfreeze`, etc.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] There are no "n" functions for deserializing these structures — the regular `thaw` and `retrieve` deserialize structures serialized with the "`n`" functions and their machine-specific equivalents.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] PHP originally implemented serialization through the built-in `serialize()` and `unserialize()` functions.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] PHP can serialize any of its data types except resources (file pointers, sockets, etc.).
[src:structured-clone/serialization] The built-in `unserialize()` function is often dangerous when used on completely untrusted data.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] For objects, there are two "magic methods" that can be implemented within a class — `__sleep()` and `__wakeup()` — that are called from within `serialize()` and `unserialize()`, respectively, that can clean up and restore an object.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] For example, it may be desirable to close a database connection on serialization and restore the connection on deserialization; this functionality would be handled in these two magic methods.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] They also permit the object to pick which properties are serialized.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] Since PHP 5.1, there is an object-oriented serialization mechanism for objects, the `Serializable` interface.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] Prolog's *term* structure, which is the only data structure of the language, can be serialized out through the built-in predicate `write_term/3` and serialized-in through the built-in predicates `read/1` and `read_term/2`.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] The resulting stream is uncompressed text (in some encoding determined by configuration of the target stream), with any free variables in the term represented by placeholder variable names.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] The predicate `write_term/3` is standardized in the ISO Specification for Prolog (ISO/IEC 13211-1) on pages 59 ff.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] Therefore it is expected that terms serialized-out by one implementation can be serialized-in by another without ambiguity or surprises.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] In practice, implementation-specific extensions (e.g.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] SWI-Prolog's dictionaries) may use non-standard term structures, so interoperability may break in edge cases.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] As examples, see the corresponding manual pages for SWI-Prolog, SICStus Prolog, GNU Prolog.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] Whether and how serialized terms received over the network are checked against a specification (after deserialization from the character stream has happened) is left to the implementer.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] Prolog's built-in Definite Clause Grammars can be applied at that stage.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] The core general serialization mechanism is the `pickle` standard library module, alluding to the database systems term *pickling* to describe data serialization (*unpickling* for *deserializing*).
[src:structured-clone/serialization] Pickle uses a simple stack-based virtual machine that records the instructions used to reconstruct the object.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] It is a cross-version customizable but unsafe (not secure against erroneous or malicious data) serialization format.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] Malformed or maliciously constructed data, may cause the deserializer to import arbitrary modules and instantiate any object.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] The standard library also includes modules serializing to standard data formats: `json` (with built-in support for basic scalar and collection types and able to support arbitrary types via encoding and decoding hooks).
[src:structured-clone/serialization] `plistlib` (with support for both binary and XML property list formats).
[src:structured-clone/serialization] `xdrlib` (with support for the External Data Representation (XDR) standard as described in RFC 1014).
[src:structured-clone/serialization] Finally, it is recommended that an object's `__repr__` be evaluable in the right environment, making it a rough match for Common Lisp's `print-object`.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] Not all object types can be pickled automatically, especially ones that hold operating system resources like file handles, but users can register custom "reduction" and construction functions to support the pickling and unpickling of arbitrary types.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] Pickle was originally implemented as the pure Python `pickle` module, but, in versions of Python prior to 3.0, the `cPickle` module (also a built-in) offers improved performance (up to 1000 times faster).
[src:structured-clone/serialization] The `cPickle` was adapted from the Unladen Swallow project.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] In Python 3, users should always import the standard version, which attempts to import the accelerated version and falls back to the pure Python version.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] R has the function `dput` which writes an ASCII text representation of an R object to a file or connection.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] A representation can be read from a file using `dget`.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] More specific, the function `serialize` serializes an R object to a connection, the output being a raw vector coded in hexadecimal format.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] The `unserialize` function allows to read an object from a connection or a raw vector.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] REBOL will serialize to file (`save/all`) or to a `string!` (`mold/all`).
[src:structured-clone/serialization] Strings and files can be deserialized using the polymorphic `load` function.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] `RProtoBuf` provides cross-language data serialization in R, using Protocol Buffers.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] Ruby includes the standard module `Marshal` with 2 methods `dump` and `load`, akin to the standard Unix utilities `dump` and `restore`.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] These methods serialize to the standard class `String`, that is, they effectively become a sequence of bytes.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] Some objects cannot be serialized (doing so would raise a `TypeError` exception): bindings, procedure objects, instances of class IO, singleton objects and interfaces.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] If a class requires custom serialization (for example, it requires certain cleanup actions done on dumping / restoring), it can be done by implementing 2 methods: `_dump` and `_load`.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] The instance method `_dump` should return a `String` object containing all the information necessary to reconstitute objects of this class and all referenced objects up to a maximum depth given as an integer parameter (a value of -1 implies that depth checking should be disabled).
[src:structured-clone/serialization] The class method `_load` should take a `String` and return an object of this class.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] `Serde` is the most widely used library, or crate, for serialization in Rust which provides the `Serialize` and `Deserialize` traits.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] In general, non-recursive and non-sharing objects can be stored and retrieved in a human readable form using the `storeOn:`/`readFrom:` protocol.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] The `storeOn:` method generates the text of a Smalltalk expression which – when evaluated using `readFrom:` – recreates the original object.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] This scheme is special, in that it uses a procedural description of the object, not the data itself.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] It is therefore very flexible, allowing for classes to define more compact representations.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] However, in its original form, it does not handle cyclic data structures or preserve the identity of shared references (i.e. two references a single object will be restored as references to two equal, but not identical copies).
[src:structured-clone/serialization] For this, various portable and non-portable alternatives exist.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] Some of them are specific to a particular Smalltalk implementation or class library.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] There are several ways in Squeak Smalltalk to serialize and store objects.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] The easiest and most used are `storeOn:/readFrom:` and binary storage formats based on `SmartRefStream` serializers.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] In addition, bundled objects can be stored and retrieved using `ImageSegments`.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] Both provide a so-called "binary-object storage framework", which support serialization into and retrieval from a compact binary form.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] Both handle cyclic, recursive and shared structures, storage/retrieval of class and metaclass info and include mechanisms for "on the fly" object migration (i.e. to convert instances which were written by an older version of a class with a different object layout).
[src:structured-clone/serialization] The APIs are similar (storeBinary/readBinary), but the encoding details are different, making these two formats incompatible.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] However, the Smalltalk/X code is open source and free and can be loaded into other Smalltalks to allow for cross-dialect object interchange.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] Object serialization is not part of the ANSI Smalltalk specification.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] As a result, the code to serialize an object varies by Smalltalk implementation.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] For instance, a serialized object created in Squeak Smalltalk cannot be restored in Ambrai Smalltalk.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] Consequently, various applications that do work on multiple Smalltalk implementations that rely on object serialization cannot share data between these different implementations.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] These applications include the MinneStore object database and some RPC packages.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] A solution to this problem is SIXX, which is a package for multiple Smalltalks that uses an XML-based format for serialization.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] The Swift standard library provides two protocols, `Encodable` and `Decodable` (composed together as `Codable`), which allow instances of conforming types to be serialized to or deserialized from JSON, property lists, or other formats.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] Default implementations of these protocols can be generated by the compiler for types whose stored properties are also `Decodable` or `Encodable`.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] PowerShell implements serialization through the built-in cmdlet `Export-CliXML`.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] `Export-CliXML` serializes .NET objects and stores the resulting XML in a file.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] To reconstitute the objects, use the `Import-CliXML` cmdlet, which generates a deserialized object from the XML in the exported file.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] Deserialized objects, often known as "property bags" are not live objects; they are snapshots that have properties, but no methods.
[src:structured-clone/serialization] Two dimensional data structures can also be (de)serialized in CSV format using the built-in cmdlets `Import-CSV` and `Export-CSV`.
[src:structured-clone/structured-clone-algorithm] The **structured clone algorithm** copies complex JavaScript objects.
[src:structured-clone/structured-clone-algorithm] It is used internally when invoking `structuredClone()`, to transfer data between Workers via `postMessage()`, storing objects with IndexedDB, or copying objects for other APIs.
[src:structured-clone/structured-clone-algorithm] It clones by recursing through the input object while maintaining a map of previously visited references, to avoid infinitely traversing cycles.
[src:structured-clone/structured-clone-algorithm] For `Error` types, the error name must be one of: `Error`, `EvalError`, `RangeError`, `ReferenceError`, `SyntaxError`, `TypeError`, `URIError` (or will be set to "Error").
[src:structured-clone/structured-clone-algorithm] Browsers must serialize the properties `name` and `message`, and are expected to serialize other "interesting" properties of the errors such as `stack`, `cause`, etc.
[src:structured-clone/structured-clone-algorithm] `AggregateError` support is expected to be added to the specification in whatwg/html#5749 (and is already supported in some browsers).
[src:structured-clone/structuredclone] This feature is well established and works across many devices and browser versions.
[src:structured-clone/structuredclone] It’s been available across browsers since March 2022.
[src:structured-clone/structuredclone] The **`structuredClone()`** method of the `Window` interface creates a deep clone of a value using the structured clone algorithm.
[src:structured-clone/structuredclone] The method also allows transferable objects in the original value to be *transferred* rather than cloned to the new object.
[src:structured-clone/structuredclone] Transferred objects are detached from the original object and attached to the new object; they are no longer accessible in the original object.
[src:structured-clone/structuredclone] Across all browsers, a direct call `structuredClone(value)` clones values in the caller's realm.
[src:structured-clone/structuredclone] From Firefox 149, web extension content scripts can call `window.structuredClone(value)` to clone values in the page's realm and `globalThis.structuredClone(value)` to clone into the realm of the content script.
[src:structured-clone/structuredclone] For more information, see `structuredClone` in content scripts.
[src:structured-clone/structuredclone] This can be any structured-cloneable type.
[src:structured-clone/structuredclone] An array of transferable objects that will be moved rather than cloned to the returned object.
[src:structured-clone/structuredclone] Thrown if any part of the input value is not serializable.
[src:structured-clone/structuredclone] This function can be used to deep copy JavaScript values.
[src:structured-clone/structuredclone] Transferable objects (only) can be transferred rather than duplicated in the cloned object, using the `transfer` property of the `options` parameter.
[src:structured-clone/structuredclone] Transferring makes the original object unusable.
[src:structured-clone/structuredclone] This code shows how to clone an array and transfer its underlying resources to the new object.
[src:structured-clone/structuredclone] On return, the original `uInt8Array.buffer` is cleared.
[src:structured-clone/structuredclone] You can clone any number of objects and transfer any subset of those objects.
[src:structured-clone/structuredclone] For example, this code transfers `arrayBuffer1` from the passed in value, but not `arrayBuffer2`.
[src:structured-clone/structuredclone] In this example, we clone an object with one member, which is an array.
[src:structured-clone/structuredclone] After cloning, changes to each object do not affect the other object.
[src:structured-clone/structuredclone] In this example we create an `ArrayBuffer` and then clone the object it is a member of, transferring the buffer.
[src:structured-clone/structuredclone] We can use the buffer in the cloned object, but if we try to use the original buffer we get an exception.
[src:structured-clone/transferable-objects] Transferring may also be used when creating deep copies of objects with `structuredClone()`.
[src:structured-clone/transferable-objects] Following the cloning operation, the transferred resources are moved rather than copied to the cloned object.
[src:structured-clone/transferable-objects] The mechanism used to transfer an object's resources depends on the object.
[src:structured-clone/transferable-objects] For example, when an `ArrayBuffer` is transferred between threads, the memory resource that it points to is *literally* moved between contexts in a fast and efficient zero-copy operation.
[src:structured-clone/transferable-objects] Other objects may be transferred by copying the associated resource and then deleting it from the old context.
[src:structured-clone/transferable-objects] A list of transferable objects is provided below.
[src:structured-clone/transferable-objects] The code below demonstrates how transferring works when sending a message from a main thread to a web worker thread.
[src:structured-clone/transferable-objects] The `Uint8Array` is copied (duplicated) in the worker while its buffer is transferred.
[src:structured-clone/transferable-objects] After transfer any attempt to read or write `uInt8Array` from the main thread will throw, but you can still check the `byteLength` to confirm it is now zero.
[src:structured-clone/transferable-objects] The code below shows a `structuredClone()` operation where the underlying buffer is copied from the original object to the clone.
[src:structured-clone/transferable-objects] Interfaces that can be transferred should include this information in their introduction.
